 and Regional Human Rights Regimes -- tChapter 17. Leveraging Norms: The ECHR and Turkey's Human Rights Reforms -- tChapter 18. Conclusion: Turkey's Prospects and Broader Implications -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTurkey's mixed human rights record has been highly politicized in the debate surrounding the country's probable ascendance to membership in the European Union. Beginning with the foundation of a secular republic in 1923, and continuing with founding membership in the United Nations and participation in the European Convention on Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms, Turkey made significant commitments to the advancement of human rights. However, its authoritarian tradition, periods of military rule, increasing social inequality, and economic crises have led to policies that undermine human rights. While legislative reforms and civil social activism since the 1980s have contributed greatly to the advancement of human rights, recent progress is threatened by the rise of nationalism, persistent gender inequality, and economic hardship.In Human Rights in Turkey, twenty-one Turkish and international scholars from various disciplines examine human rights policies and conditions since the 1920s, at the intersection of domestic and international politics, as they relate to all spheres of life in Turkey. A wide range of rights, such as freedom of the press and religion, minority, women's, and workers' rights, and the right to education, are examined in the context of the history and current conditions of the Republic of Turkey.In light of the events of September 11, 2001, and subsequent developments in the Middle East, recent proposals about modeling other Muslim countries after Turkey add urgency to an in-depth study of Turkish politics and the causal links with human rights. The scholarship presented in Human Rights in Turkey holds significant implications for the study of human rights in the Middle East and around the globe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCivil rightszTurkey. 0aHuman rightszTurkey. 4aHuman Rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aPolitical Science.1 aArat, Zehra F. Kabasakal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDenli, Özlem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEcevit, Yιldιz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalk, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalk, Richard.1 aGök, Fatma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIlgaz, Deniz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacolly, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKabasakal Arat, Zehra F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirişçi, Kemal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO\x27Neil, Mary Lou, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOner, Sera, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOran, Baskιn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOzerdem, Alpaslan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Thomas W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaşatar Parlak, N Burcu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTürkmen, Füsun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeisband, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYannas, Prodromos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a